      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at our quarterly reports for the electronics warehouse and our shrinkage numbers are way higher than usual. i need to figure out how this unexpected loss is going to mess with our inventory turnover ratio. can you help me with the math on how to factor shrinkage into the turnover calculation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, an unrecorded loss, is like a small, sneaky piece of stolen goods that keeps your inventory from being as plentiful as it should be. You need to account for it before you can calculate a proper inventory turnover ratio, or your numbers will look suspiciously good. A good, honest inventory turnover ratio is what you want, not one that's hiding a hole in the wall where some inventory went.\n\nHere's the basic math, but don't let the numbers scare you. Shrinkage is a real problem, and it's a very messy problem, much like trying to herd a flock of particularly slippery, ill-tempered inventory goblins.\n\nThe standard Inventory Turnover Ratio is:\n\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nThe problem is that your **Average Inventory** is inflated because it includes the lost items. To fix this, you need to adjust your inventory figure to reflect what *should* be there.\n\nHere is how you factor in shrinkage:\n\n1.  **Calculate Adjusted Inventory:** Take your reported ending inventory and subtract the estimated shrinkage for that period.\n    $$\\text{Adjust",
